        <h2>Including the files</h2>
        <p>
            Now I simply included the links to the files in my header and that was it for that. Also I've recently started organising all external files into a libraries folder. Where I keep well all of my libraries, keeps things nice and neat. Shown below the code I included in my header.
        </p>
        <pre class="brush: xml">
            <!-- Syntax Highlighter -->
                <script type="text/javascript" src="/libraries/syntaxhighlighter/shCore.js"></script>
                <script type="text/javascript" src="/libraries/syntaxhighlighter/shBrushXml.js"></script>
                <script type="text/javascript" src="/libraries/syntaxhighlighter/shBrushJScript.js"></script>
                <script type="text/javascript" src="/libraries/syntaxhighlighter/shBrushCss.js"></script>

                <link href="/libraries/syntaxhighlighter/shCore.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css"/>
                <link href="/libraries/syntaxhighlighter/shThemeDefault.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css"/>
        </pre>
        <p>
            Once that was done I just needed to test it out. There are two methods for using the library, I decided to go with the <code>pre</code> method, as it is much cleaner and simpler. Here a test, an example of some code below using the JavaScript brush:
        </p>
        <pre class="brush: js">
            // This is a test
            let index = ["BDic_2ALinker", "BDic_activator", "BDic_agar", "BDic_agaropectin", "BDic_agarose", "BDic_ahl", "BDic_allostericRegulation", "BDic_alphaVirus", "BDic_amphipathic", "BDic_amphoteric"]

            for(let i = 0; i &lt; index.length; i++) {
                console.log(index[i]);
            }
        </pre>
        <h2>Using the library</h2>
        <p>
            Note that when the pre method is used in conjunction with the js brush, you must convert all less than symbols, &lt;, to the actual HTML code written as &amp;lt;. Once that is done, include the following elements with the appropriate class attribute to specify the brush to use.
        </p>
        <pre class="brush: xml">
            <!-- Use the pre element tags with the appropriate class, shown below. -->
            <pre class="brush: js">
                // Your code goes here!
                let index = ["BDic_2ALinker", "BDic_activator", "BDic_agar", "BDic_agaropectin", "BDic_agarose", "BDic_ahl", "BDic_allostericRegulation", "BDic_alphaVirus", "BDic_amphipathic", "BDic_amphoteric"]
    
                for(let i = 0; i &lt; index.length; i++) {
                    console.log(index[i]);
                }
            </pre>

            <!-- You must also include the following script at the bottom of your page below the pre elements
            This so that the library executes, shown: -->

                <script type="text/javascript">
                    SyntaxHighlighter.all()
                </script>
        </pre>
        <p>
            That's it! That's how you install and use <a href="http://alexgorbatchev.com/SyntaxHighlighter/">SyntaxHighlighter</a>!
        </p>

